    <section id="sect-00004">
    <title>Comparison operators</title>
    <para id="para-00021"><span class="red-code">Programmers often have to answer questions like "</span>Is the current user the admin?<span class="red-code">"</span> A programmer may want to compare a string variable, user, to the string, "admin". <term id="term-00003">Comparison operators</term> are used to compare values, and the result is either True or False. Ex: is_admin = (user == "admin"). user is compared with "admin" using the == operator, which tests for equality. The boolean variable, is_admin, is assigned with the boolean result.</para>
    <para id="para-00022">The 6 comparison operators:
    <list id="list-00003">
    <item><term id="term-00004">==</term> : equal to</item>
    <item><term id="term-00005">!=</term> : not equal to</item>
    <item><term id="term-00006">></term> : greater than</item>
    <item><term id="term-00007">&lt;</term> : less than</item>
    <item><term id="term-00008">>=</term> : greater than or equal to</item>
    <item><term id="term-00009">&lt;=</term> : less than or equal to</item>
    </list></para>
